</span>

</figure><div class="os-caption-container"><span class="os-title-label">Figure </span><span class="os-number">21.3</span><span class="os-divider"> </span><span class="os-divider"> </span><span class="os-caption">The binding energy per nucleon is largest for nuclides with mass number of approximately 56.</span></div></div>
<div data-type="example" id="fs-idp47733552"><h3 class="os-title"><span class="os-title-label">Example </span><span class="os-number">21.3</span><span class="os-divider"> </span></h3>
<p id="fs-idm62997744"><span data-type="title">Calculation of Binding Energy per Nucleon</span>The iron nuclide <math display="inline"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mrow/><mn>26</mn><mn>56</mn></msubsup><mtext>Fe</mtext></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><msubsup><mrow/><mn>26</mn><mn>56</mn></msubsup><mtext>Fe</mtext></annotation-xml></semantics></math> lies near the top of the binding energy curve (<a class="autogenerated-content" href="#CNX_Chem_21_01_BindEnergy">Figure 21.3</a>) and is one of the most stable nuclides. What is the binding energy per nucleon (in MeV) for the nuclide <math display="inline"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mn>26</mn></mrow><mn>56</mn></msubsup><mtext>Fe</mtext></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mn>26</mn></mrow><mn>56</mn></msubsup><mtext>Fe</mtext></annotation-xml></semantics></math> (atomic mass of 55.9349 amu)?</p><p id="fs-idp15576576"><span data-type="title">Solution</span>As in <a class="autogenerated-content" href="#fs-idm18254784">Example 21.2</a>, we first determine the mass defect of the nuclide, which is the difference between the mass of 26 protons, 30 neutrons, and 26 electrons, and the observed mass of an <math display="inline"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mn>26</mn></mrow><mn>56</mn></msubsup><mtext>Fe</mtext></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mn>26</mn></mrow><mn>56</mn></msubsup><mtext>Fe</mtext></annotation-xml></semantics></math> atom:</p><div data-type="equation" id="fs-idm131278944"><math display="block"><semantics><mrow><mtable columnalign="left"><mtr><mtd><mtext>Mass defect</mtext><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>26</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>1.0073 amu</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>30</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mtext>1.0087 amu</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>26</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>0.00055 amu</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>−</mo><mtext>55.9349 amu</mtext></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mtext>56.4651 amu</mtext><mo>−</mo><mtext>55.9349 amu</mtext></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mtext>0.5302 amu</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mtable columnalign="left"><mtr><mtd><mtext>Mass defect</mtext><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>[</mo><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>26</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>1.0073 amu</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>30</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mtext>1.0087 amu</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>26</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>0.00055 amu</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>]</mo></mrow><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>−</mo><mtext>55.9349 amu</mtext></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mtext>56.4651 amu</mtext><mo>−</mo><mtext>55.9349 amu</mtext></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mtext>0.5302 amu</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></annotation-xml></semantics></math></div>
<p id="fs-idp91322720">We next calculate the binding energy for one nucleus from the mass defect using the mass-energy equivalence equation:</p>
<div data-type="equation" id="fs-idp90560128"><math display="block"><semantics><mrow><mtable columnalign="left"><mtr/><mtr/><mtr><mtd><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mtext>0.5302 amu</mtext><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.6605</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>−27</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>kg</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>1 amu</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mspace width="0.3em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>2.998</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mn>8</mn></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>m/s</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mn>7.913</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>−11</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>kg</mtext><mtext>⋅</mtext><msup><mtext>m/s</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mn>7.913</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>−11</mn></mrow></msup><mtext>J</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mtable columnalign="left"><mtr/><mtr/><mtr><mtd><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mtext>0.5302 amu</mtext><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.6605</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>−27</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>kg</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>1 amu</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mspace width="0.3em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mn>2.998</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mn>8</mn></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>m/s</mtext></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mn>7.913</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>−11</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>kg</mtext><mtext>⋅</mtext><msup><mtext>m/s</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>=</mo><mn>7.913</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mn>−11</mn></mrow></msup><mtext>J</mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></annotation-xml></semantics></math></div>
<p id="fs-idp148855104">We then convert the binding energy in joules per nucleus into units of MeV per nuclide:</p>
<div data-type="equation" id="fs-idm54914048"><math display="block"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>7.913</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>−11</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mtext>1 MeV</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>1.602</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>−13</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>=</mo><mtext>493.9 MeV</mtext></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mn>7.913</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>−11</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mtext>1 MeV</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>1.602</mn><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>×</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>−13</mn></mrow></msup><mspace width="0.2em"/><mtext>J</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>=</mo><mtext>493.9 MeV</mtext></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></div>
<p id="fs-idp84501712">Finally, we determine the binding energy per nucleon by dividing the total nuclear binding energy by the number of nucleons in the atom:</p>
<div data-type="equation" id="fs-idp136767392"><math display="block"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mtext>Binding energy per nucleon</mtext><mo>=</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mtext>493.9 MeV</mtext></mrow><mn>56</mn></mfrac><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>=</mo><mtext>8.820 MeV/nucleon</mtext></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><mtext>Binding energy per nucleon</mtext><mo>=</mo><mspace width="0.2em"/><mfrac><mrow><mtext>493.9 MeV</mtext></mrow><mn>56</mn></mfrac><mspace width="0.2em"/><mo>=</mo><mtext>8.820 MeV/nucleon</mtext></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></div>
<p id="fs-idm37662944">Note that this is almost 25% larger than the binding energy per nucleon for <math display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mn>4</mn></msubsup><mtext>He</mtext><mo>.</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mn>4</mn></msubsup><mtext>He</mtext><mo>.</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></p><p id="fs-idp8906016">(Note also that this is the same process as in <a class="autogenerated-content" href="#fs-idp85198000">Example 21.1</a>, but with the additional step of dividing the total nuclear binding energy by the number of nucleons.)</p>
<p id="fs-idp90415648"><span data-type="title">Check Your Learning</span>What is the binding energy per nucleon in <math display="inline"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mspace width="0.5em"/><mn>9</mn></mrow><mn>19</mn></msubsup><mtext>F</mtext></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><msubsup><mrow/><mrow><mspace width="0.5em"/><mn>9</mn></mrow><mn>19</mn></msubsup><mtext>F</mtext></annotation-xml></semantics></math> (atomic mass, 18.9984 amu)?</p><div data-type="note" id="fs-idm62295296"><h3 class="os-title" data-type="title"><span class="os-title-label" data-type="" id="[redacted for uniqueness]">Answer:</span></h3><div class="os-note-body">
<p id="fs-idm46993968">7.810 MeV/nucleon</p>
</div></div>
